---

# Final Recommendation

Source B is the most credible because it is written by qualified researchers, has undergone peer review, presents evidence from multiple clinical trials, and discusses both benefits and limitations rather than making unsupported claims.

Sources A and C may provide opinions or personal experiences, but they should not be relied upon as primary evidence due to their lack of verifiable sources and balanced analysis.

---

# Reflection

## What I Learned

A source should not be judged solely by how convincing it sounds. Factors such as author expertise, supporting evidence, peer review, objectivity, and publication quality are essential when evaluating credibility.

---

## What I'd Do Differently

Compare multiple peer-reviewed studies instead of relying on a single research paper to gain a broader understanding of the topic and identify any conflicting evidence.

